Class DefRef

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.vector.cfg.model.access.DefRef
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    TypedDefRef

    @PublishedApi(value=ADDITIONS_ALLOWED)
public class DefRef
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.io.Serializable

    The DefRef class represents an AUTOSAR definition reference (e.g. /MICROSAR/CanIf) without a connection to any model. A DefRef replaces the String which represents a definition reference. You shall always use a DefRef instance, when you want to reference something by it's definition.

    The class abstracts the behavior of definition references in the AUTOSAR model (e.g. AUTOSAR 3 and AUTOSAR 4 handling).

    DefRefs are constant; their values can not be changed after they are created. All DefRef classes are immutable.

    A DefRef represents the definition reference as two parts:

    • Package part - e.g. /MICROSAR
    • Definition without the package part - e.g. CanIf/CanIfGeneral
    This is used to navigate through the AUTOSAR model with refinements and wildcards. So you have to create a DefRef with the two parts separated.

    The figure shows the structure of the DefRef class and its sub classes.
    Creation
    You can create a DefRef object with following public static methods (partial):
    • DefRef.create(DefRef, String) - Parent DefRef, Child name
    • DefRef.create(IDefRefWildcard, String) - Wildcard, Definition without package
    • DefRef.create(MIHasDefinition) - Model object
    • DefRef.create(MIHasDefinition, String) - Parent object, Child name
    • DefRef.create(MIParamConfMultiplicity) - Definition object
    • DefRef.create(String, String) - Package part, Definition without package
    Wildcards
    DefRef instances can also have a wildcard instead of a package String (IDefRefWildcard). The wildcard is used to match on multiple packages.
    Useful Methods
    This section describes some useful methods (Please look at the javadoc of the DefRef class for a full documentation):
    • defRef.isDefinitionOf(MIHasDefinition) - Checks the definition of the configuration element and returns true if the element has the definition. The "defRef" object is e.g. from the Constants class.
      • Note: The method isDefinitionOf() returns false, if the element is removed or invisible.
    • defRef.asDefinitionOf(MIHasDefinition, Class<>) - Checks the definition of the configuration element and returns the element casted to the configuration subtype, or null.
      • Note: The method asDefinitionOf() returns null, if the element is removed or invisible.
     
 MIObject yourObject = ...;
 DefRef yourDefRef = ...;

 if(yourDefRef.isDefinitionOf(yourObject){
      //It is the correct instance
      //Do something
 }

 //Or with an integrated cast in the TypedDefRef case
 final MIContainer container = yourDefRef.asDefinitionOf(yourObject);
 if(container  != null){
      //Do something
 }

    The create(MIHasDefinition) and create(MIParamConfMultiplicity) support the IMockProvider interface. See IMockProvider for more details.

      • asDefinitionOf

        @PublishedMethod
public <T extends com.vector.cfg.model.mdf.model.autosar.ecucdescription.MIHasDefinition> T asDefinitionOf(MIObject modelObject,
                                                                                                                             java.lang.Class<T> classToCheck)
        Checks if this object is the definition of the passed modelObject and an instance of classToCheck. If the check is true, the method returns the object casted to classToCheck. Otherwise the method return null.

        Note: This method tests also refinements. So, if the modelObject is refined of this definition, it will also yield to true.

        Note: This method is an implicit null and classToCheck class check. This means, if it returns true, the modelObject is an instance of classToCheck.

        The method will return null, if the passed modelObject is removed. The method will return null, if the passed modelObject is invisible.

        Parameters:
        modelObject - The modelObject to check.
        classToCheck - The class which the modelObject must be an instance of.
        Returns:
        object, if this is the definition of the modelObject and it is instance of classToCheck. Otherwise null.
        Throws:
        java.lang.NullPointerException -
        • if the classToCheck is null
        See Also:
        isDefinitionOf(MIObject, Class)

      • createReplacedRefinementDefRefFrom

        @PublishedMethod
public DefRef createReplacedRefinementDefRefFrom(DefRef refinementParentDefRef)
        Creates a new DefRef with a replaced package and module shortname from the data of the passed refinementParentDefRef is replaced and the suffix of the original DefRef (this) is used. So the path of this is replaced with the package and module of refinementParentDefRef and a new DefRef is returned.

        Code example: 

         
        DefRef myDef = DefRef.create("/MyPkg", "MyCDD/CddContainer");
        DefRef autosarDef = DefRef.create(DefRef.AUTOSAR4_PACKAGE, "Cdd");

  //Caution: You have to check refinements before calling createReplacedRefinementDefRefOf
  if(myDef.isRefinedOf(autosarDef, ma)){

            DefRef replaced = myDef.createReplacedRefinementDefRefOf(autosarDef);
            //the replaced DefRef will be "/AUTOSAR/EcucDefs/Cdd/CddContainer" instead of "/MyPkg/MyCDD/CddContainer"
        }

        Also note that the Module shortname is also replaced. So strange shortnames names are correctly changed to the correct shortname of the parent refinement. E.g. CDD => Cdd.

        Caution: The this DefRefs Module DefRef must be refined of the passed refinementParentModuleDefRef, otherwise the method will lead to unpredictable results. So you have to check myDefRef.isRefinedOf(parent, ma);

        Parameters:
        refinementParentDefRef - The DefRef from which the packages and the Module shortname are retrieved. This must not be the same element path. It could simply be the Module DefRef.
        Returns:
        A new created DefRef with the package info and module of passed defRef and the DefRef path of this.
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException -
        • if the refinementParentDefRef is null
        • if this has wildcards
